<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,341,1194]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,339,424,450]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name denotes the sandy habitat of this species, from Greek: ammos = sand, philos = loving.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="26" pageNumber="27" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="26.[151,1437,341,1194]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,351,508,534]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Description.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[361,457,509,534]" italics="true" pageId="26" pageNumber="27">Female.</emphasis>
Carapace brown, eyes encircled with black, labium and sternum yellow. Rebordered labium wider than long. Chelicerae with two pro- and one retromarginal teeth. Opisthosoma generally beige coloured with dark dorsal pattern (Fig. 
<number box="[675,707,589,615]" pageId="26" pageNumber="27" value="67.0">67</number>
); venter with large median light patch.
</paragraph>
